Span.Text: BI has taken off tremendously in the NHS in the past few years.  It can provide actionable intelligent data, for frontline staff and managers, to make real changes.  However, implementation, data linkage and maintaining software can be extremely difficult and costly.  Using familiar coding and Microsoft based products ensures sustainability in-house and keeps external contractors costs to a minimum.

Mine disparate information systems to build more accurate and richer patient profiles. With the ability to fuse structured data (e.g., electronic health records) with unstructured data (e.g., handwritten case notes), you can uncover previously hidden intelligence.
Glean insight quickly from multiple data types

Optimise diagnosis and treatment using highly intuitive, interactive data exploration, visualisation and presentation for all health professional skill levels. Ask questions in a natural-language speech bubble, and Microsoft Excel answers by generating appropriate data visualisations.
Working together is easy with integrated sharing capabilities in Excel. Post analyses to social networks, present findings online or send workbooks via instant message.

Uncover unexpected patterns and associations and develop models to anticipate emerging health trends. Use predictive data to develop targeted population health strategies and help cut health costs at city, provider and systemic levels.
"Linking data for analyses was something we couldn’t do before. With Power BI, it’s simple. Power BI makes the hard things easy. Everything becomes possible."
Professor Philip Dean, Head of Department of Pharmacy and Quality Control Laboratory Services,
North Tees and Hartlepool National Health Services Trust
UK Hospital Sees Cloud-Based BI Service as a Tool to Boost Clinical Outcomes and Efficiency
